## Disadvantages and Challenges of Self-Driving Cars

### 1. **Technological Limitations and Safety Concerns**

Despite advancements, self-driving technology is not yet foolproof. There have been high-profile accidents involving autonomous vehicles, such as the fatal Uber crash in 2018, which have undermined public confidence ([FPT Software, 2019](https://www.fpt-software.com/pros-and-cons-of-self-driving-vehicles/); [Scholastic, 2017](https://junior.scholastic.com/issues/2017-18/112017/are-driverless-cars-a-good-idea.html)). Software glitches, sensor failures, and challenges in adverse weather conditions (e.g., heavy rain or snow) remain significant hurdles. The complexity of the software—often containing over 100 million lines of code—requires rigorous testing and validation to avoid fatal errors ([Design News, 2018](https://www.designnews.com/electronics-test/self-driving-cars-reliability-challenges-solutions-and-social-adoption)).

### 2. **Cybersecurity and Privacy Risks**

Self-driving cars are highly connected devices vulnerable to hacking and cyberattacks. Unauthorized access could lead to vehicle theft, accidents, or breaches of personal data. Surveys indicate that 67% of Americans are concerned about cybersecurity threats related to autonomous vehicles ([Identity Management Institute, n.d.](https://identitymanagementinstitute.org/self-driving-car-security/)). The protection of user data and vehicle systems is a critical area requiring ongoing regulatory and technological attention.

### 3. **Ethical and Moral Dilemmas**

Autonomous vehicles must be programmed to make complex ethical decisions in unavoidable accident scenarios, often referred to as the "trolley problem." Deciding how to allocate risk and harm raises profound moral questions that society has yet to fully resolve ([The Conversation, 2021](https://theconversation.com/us/topics/driverless-cars-11740)). These dilemmas complicate the development of universally accepted operational protocols.

### 4. **Economic and Social Disruptions**

The widespread adoption of self-driving cars could lead to massive job losses in driving-related sectors, including truck drivers, taxi drivers, and delivery personnel ([Negretti & Associates, n.d.](https://negrettilaw.com/news/self-driving-cars-pros-and-cons/); [University of Huddersfield, 2015](http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/33924/)). Additionally, the transition requires heavy investments in infrastructure upgrades and legal frameworks to accommodate autonomous vehicles.

### 5. **Public Acceptance and Trust**

Despite technological progress, many consumers remain hesitant to trust self-driving cars. A 2018 AAA survey found that 54% of Americans felt unsafe sharing roads with autonomous vehicles ([Design News, 2018](https://www.designnews.com/electronics-test/self-driving-cars-reliability-challenges-solutions-and-social-adoption)). Building public confidence through transparent safety records and regulatory oversight is essential for widespread adoption.

